We first extract the relevant values from the statements (using the end‐of‐period amounts):

1. Current Ratio = Total Current Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
  = 9,982,261.98 / 499,821.72 ≈ 19.96

2. Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (2,272,433.90 / 3,956,433.90) × 100 ≈ 57.45%

3. Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  The only liabilities shown are current liabilities (Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable) giving a total of 499,821.72.  
  = 499,821.72 / 14,890,758.71 ≈ 0.03

4. Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (1,390,936.99 / 3,956,433.90) × 100 ≈ 35.16%

5. Cash to Current Debt Ratio = (Cash on Hand + Bank Deposits) / Total Current Liabilities  
  Cash on Hand + Bank Deposits = 2,103,508.95 + 4,714,000.00 = 6,817,508.95  
  = 6,817,508.95 / 499,821.72 ≈ 13.64

6. Free Cash Flow (FCF) = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities – Capital Expenditures  
  Here, the cash flow from operating activities is –1,182,491.05 and there was no purchase of fixed assets (Capital Expenditures = 0.00)  
  = –1,182,491.05

7. Return on Assets (ROA) = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100  
  = (1,390,936.99 / 14,890,758.71) × 100 ≈ 9.34%

Thus, the final solution in the required json format is:

    "Cash to Current Debt Ratio": "13.64",
    "Free Cash Flow (FCF)": "-1182491.05",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "9.34%"
  }
}
